Text.Value: Leave.
Aradin ran off.
Indeed - I'll survive a sore jaw. This grove has bigger problems right now.
I wouldn't have looked to a drow for help, but I'm grateful all the same. I'm Zevlor.

Text.Value: I can see that. You're lucky your little display scared him off.

EditorData.NodeContext: Brushing off Aradin like a bloodsucking fly

Text.Value: Zevlor. Now unless you plan on striking me again, I have other problems to attend to.
Let's not forget why we're here. No point in wasting precious time on a lost cause.
A cheap shot. I should've expected that.

EditorData.NodeContext: Disgust in his voice. His idiot enemy clocked him.

Text.Value: I need a healer.
Let me guess: Your old neighbours called you 'devilkin' and acted like they never knew you.
Very noble of you. Now unless you plan on striking me again, I have other problems to attend to.

Is there a place for tieflings anywhere?
I'm [GEN_PlayerName_c11eee1e-7815-6143-7233-f2427799fa53].
I'll survive a sore jaw. What I won't tolerate is a stranger waltzing in here and interfering in our business.
A cheap shot - to be expected from a drow. But you helped us, so instead of killing you, I'll just ask:

EditorData.NodeContext: Sneering, barely keeping his temper in check

Text.Value: We're raised to fear the drow, but you've earned your place here. I'll make sure everyone here knows that.

Text.Value: If it's not too serious, you could try his apprentice, Nettie. She's with the other druids, in the inner grove.

EditorData.NodeContext: Thinking, trying to help - but not holding out much hope for your chances

Text.Value: Aradin ran off.
Who in the Nine Hells do you think you are?

EditorData.NodeContext: absolutely seething

Text.Value: Outsiders, perhaps. But not me.
I'll find her. And I'll speak to Kagha while I'm there.
Found sanctuary here, did you?
Did I, now? It makes no matter - this grove has problems enough.

EditorData.NodeContext: Not interested in the player giving out to him.

Text.Value: But we can't get there with those beasts blocking our path.
This attack will only strengthen their resolve.

EditorData.NodeContext: Grim, foreboding - and tired

Text.Value: They've started a ritual to cut the grove off from the world outside.
We thought we'd found sanctuary here, but the druids have determined to turn us out.
If your people survived that, they'll survive anything.
We'd owe you a great debt. What little we have, we'll scrape together. It isn't coin we need - it's time.

EditorData.NodeContext: Accepting your request for payment for helping him

Text.Value: Whatever your business, I'd see to it quickly - the druids are forcing everyone out.

EditorData.NodeContext: Cautionary - his people are also being forced out

Text.Value: There have been several attacks by different monsters. The druids blame us 'outsiders' for drawing them here. Nobody's welcome anymore.

EditorData.NodeContext: Explaning a serious situation - the mention of 'outsiders' is bitter - his people always get blamed for everything

Text.Value: Why are they forcing you out?
I'm [GEN_PlayerName_c11eee1e-7815-6143-7233-f2427799fa53].
Leave.
Those goblins - have there been many attacks like that?
Turning your back on the needy to save your own skin? Maybe we'll get along after all.

EditorData.NodeContext: 1st line - mock shock. 2nd - jolly

Text.Value: Then you'll have better luck looting the goblins outside - this is a druids' grove.

EditorData.NodeContext: Not offered as a serious suggestion, more to underline just how unwelcoming this place is.

Text.Value: *'The Descent' - an infernal conspiracy that had seen the entire city of Elturel briefly dragged to the Hells.*
Forgive that display. Aradin's a blowhard, but that's no cause for me to join him.

EditorData.NodeContext: Directly after a confrontation in which he lost his temper with an idiot. Regaining his composure, regretting the outburst.

Text.Value: We'd owe you a great debt. If we're forced to leave now, we won't make it to the city.

EditorData.NodeContext: Grateful

Text.Value: What are you offering for my aid?
So I hoped. But we've lost so many already - and more will die if we're forced out again.

EditorData.NodeContext: Weary

Text.Value: I meant no insult. It's simply that yours are a people at war with themselves - I've never known them to care for outsiders.

EditorData.NodeContext: Seeking to explain his comment rather than offend

Text.Value: Now that's settled.

EditorData.NodeContext: Slowly and thoughtfully - considering you, idea just occurring to him

Text.Value: Perhaps you could persuade her. For more time to prepare, if nothing else.
Lucky for you, you seem to have spooked that adventurer trash into leaving.
What I didn't expect was help out there from a drow. Thank you - I'm Zevlor.

EditorData.NodeContext: Slightly surprised at himself - you're of a species that typically slaughters his kind, but you helped him instead

Text.Value: Perhaps if you could help me find a healer.

EditorData.NodeContext: Mildly concerned, grows bitter at mention of Aradin/adventurers

Text.Value: Thank you for your help out there. I'm Zevlor.

EditorData.NodeContext: Turning his attention to you, formally thanking you for helping them

Text.Value: It seems you're of a mind with our hosts here. But their ritual will force you out, too.

Text.Value: What is this place?

Afterwards, people looked at us and just saw 'devilkin'. No different from the druids here, really.

EditorData.NodeContext: Suppressing anger

Text.Value: 'The Descent'? What is that?

This place is in enough turmoil. It will be smart for both of us to make allies of enemies.

EditorData.NodeContext: Calming himself down - he's willing to let the fight go if you are

Text.Value: I was there, you know. I'd hoped you'd had a happy ending.
Hah - a fair point. We can only hope the citizens of Baldur's Gate are more open-minded.

EditorData.NodeContext: Bitter amusement

Text.Value: You had that coming.
Lucky you.

EditorData.NodeContext: Vaguely sarcastic

Text.Value: If you'll excuse me - I'd best get my people moving.

EditorData.NodeContext: Ending conversation, wearily turning back to his business

Text.Value: Oh, and if it's of any concern... you're brave to walk around without hiding your heritage. I'll make sure everyone knows that you helped us at the gate.

Text.Value: Lucky for us, a group of adventurers found a way to bring the city back.
Kagha's a piece of work. Let's see if your wit surpasses your might.
I want to try and help. I'll do what I can.
I'll see what I can do.
You had that coming.

Text.Value: Thank you again for your help out there.

Text.Value: Enough about the ritual. I have my own problems.
Aradin didn't make it? Pity - but he might've got more of my people killed, if not for you.
And so will you, if you ever lay hands on me again. That I promise you.

EditorData.NodeContext: Not interested in the player giving out to him.

Text.Value: Just keep your fists to yourself, yes?

EditorData.NodeContext: Wry but hint of warning - we started our relationship with this man by punching him in the face. He's cautiously welcoming us.

Text.Value: You were heading for bloodshed. I avoided that.
I'll survive a sore jaw. Particularly if it's rid the grove of Aradin.

I take my thanks in coin.
Well met, by whatever name. Though I'm afraid that's all the welcome we can give you.

EditorData.NodeContext: Accepting your humility, still grateful

Text.Value: You're wounded? The druid Halsin's a renowned healer, but he went with those adventurers. It seems they left him behind.

EditorData.NodeContext: Mildly concerned, grows bitter at mention of Aradin/adventurers

Bah. We've no time to offer aid to every whimpering pup.
You acted quickly. I'm just sorry I didn't get there first.

Better that than further bloodshed.

True to form, and good riddance. This grove has troubles enough.

Text.Value: Are you all right?

Text.Value: We're refugees from Elturel - we took shelter here after gnolls attacked us on the road.

Synopsis: In these dialogues, Zevlor reflects on what's happened (an attack of goblins at the gate, which the player helped with) and his mistrust of and bitterness towards the druids who are reluctantly hosting his people. He is exasperated, furious, but also eager to meet anyone who could help. He'll show a flash of anger and frustration at the start if the player struck him, but is pragmatic enough to calm himself once he realises you could be more help to him than harm.
